Not really, since the Python 2 version is a keyword, and not a function, you can&#x27;t simply provide keyword arguments to it. You would instead have to build up a string and eval it. It would have to be something like this (completely untested):<p><pre><code>    def print_wrapper(*args, **kwargs)
        outfile = None
        print_stmt = &quot;print &quot;
        if &#x27;file&#x27; in kwargs:
            outfile = open(kwargs[&#x27;file&#x27;], &#x27;a&#x27;)
            print_stmt += &#x27;>>outfile &#x27;
        print_stmt += &quot;, &quot;.join(*args)
        if &#x27;end&#x27; in kwargs and kwargs[&#x27;end&#x27;] == &#x27; &#x27;:
            print_stmt += &#x27;,&#x27;
        eval(print_stmt)
        if outfile is not None: outfile.close()
</code></pre>
sep and other end values for anything other than &#x27; &#x27; would not be possible.<p><a href"http://docs.python.org/2.6/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-print-statemen" rel"nofollo">http://docs.python.org/2.6/reference/simple_stmts.html#the-p...</a>
